2-04-05 21:38:00','<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nHow did you first get into the business of projections and interactivity and how did TMM get founded?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Brodie:</h3>\r\nWe first found an interest in projections in early 2005 during somewhat of the guerilla marketing boom. With our background in film, it was a natural transition to projection advertising. We envisioned projection advertising on a larger scale, not just guerilla but as a clear substitute to billboards.\r\n<p class=\"spacer\">It was about utilizing what was there. Interactivity was something that we almost stumbled upon as an integration into our media services. It\'s now evolved into a full department and technical team here. TMM was founded by myself and Brad Foster, with visions of non-traditional advertising.</p>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"right\" src=\"http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/tmm-feel.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"450\" height=\"299\" />\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nWhat are some of the projects that you are currently working on?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Brodie:</h3>\r\nWe just launched a huge night projection campaign with NBC for the NHL All-Star weekend in multiple US markets in addition to financial sector clients, and some alcohol brands at the moment.\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nHow did you manage to get your hands on the rare Lamborghini Reventon for the exclusive projection mapping event \"<a title=\"The Lamborghini Project\" href=\"http://vimeo.com/33167496\" target=\"_blank\">The Lamborghini Project</a>\"? Did anyone from TMM get the chance to take it for a spin?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Brodie:</h3>\r\n<p class=\"spacer\">This was not a fluke but a rare window of opportunity. We had originally planned to use a white Lamborghini SV, which was sold to a new owner and the Reventon happened to be the backup. I know its wrong for me to say a Reventon was the backup but it was. The project was with SR Auto Group who supplied the Reventon to us. None of us had the chance to drive it unfortunately but the reason behind that is because there are only 20 in the world. It also only had 300 km\'s on it and is really used as an art piece or collectors item.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote class=\"full-width line-2 line-2-after\">“Work hard, content is king and don\'t accept no, ever!”</blockquote>\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nWhat are some of the exciting things coming up for TMM in 2012?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Brodie:</h3>\r\nContinuing to push the envelope with projection projects, more interactive campaigns, mapping of buildings, objects, automobiles and of course our interactive windows program.\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nWith offices in Vancouver and Toronto where are you looking to expand to next?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Brodie:</h3>\r\n<p class=\"spacer\">We have a US venture called TMMSB in New York with shipping depots in Chicago and LA which is keeping us pretty maxed right now. Brazil is in the sites as well. We\'re hoping to be set up there for the World Cup and the Olympics in addition to China and potentially London.</p>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"full-width\" src=\"http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/tmm-lamborghini.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\n<div class=\"caption full-width\">1 of 20 Lamborghini Reventons in the world</div>\r\n<h3 class=\"question clear-left\">Asher:</h3>\r\nWith clients like Shell and Red Bull, can you see TMM doing something for Formula 1 in the future?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\n<p class=\"spacer\">Hoping so. Before we started TMM, Brad and I ran a production company focused on automotive filmmaking so we\'re all big car fans here. We had a tent alongside the track for F1 in Montreal this past year and it really changed our lives. Our team was there for a projection mapping installation celebrating Shell Canada\'s 100-year anniversary at the Formula 1 Grand Prix. I can promise that we\'ll continue to push the envelope and work with leading brands to change the media landscape.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nHow did your new creative partnership with Crush Inc. come about and in what ways will this help build The MM brand?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Brodie:</h3>\r\nWe\'re really excited about the creative partnership with Crush. They initially reached out to us as they wanted to work with projection and interactive based mediums and we\'re now able to offer our clients the whole package from creative development to campaign execution.\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nFinally, what\'s your advice to creatives wanting to expand their client base and get their work out there?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Brodie:</h3>\r\nWork hard, content is king and don\'t accept no, ever!','Brodie Gunning','','inherit','open','open','','102-autosave','','','2012-04-05 14:38:00','2012-04-05 21:38:00','',102,'http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/102-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(71,1,'2012-03-04 08:46:43','2012-03-04 08:46:43','','Interview Custom Fields','','inherit','open','open','','acf_interview-custom-fields-6','','','2012-03-04 08:46:43','2012-03-04 08:46:43','',31,'http://spiraldesign.ca/acf_interview-custom-fields-6/',0,'revision','',0),(72,1,'2012-03-04 08:50:58','2012-03-04 08:50:58','<div><img class=\"right\" src=\"http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/glenallsop.tumblr-2.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"360\" height=\"540\" /></div>\r\n<div class=\"caption right\" style=\"width: 360px;\">Afternoon light in Soho</div>\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nYou’re now living and working in NYC, where are you from originally and what brought you to NYC?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\nAbout a year and a half ago New York photographer Christian Oth skyped me one day in my Whale Beach treehouse (Sydney, Australia) - he told me to get a haircut and come and shoot for him. Couldn\'t say no. His tight-knit team of photogs are all legends in their own fields but come together under the \'<a title=\"Christian Oth Studio NYC\" href=\"http://www.christianothstudio.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Christian Oth Studio</a>\' banner to document New York &amp; destination weddings.\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nHow did you get started in Photography and when did you decide it was what you wanted to do for a living?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\nI started shooting when my dad got sick 7 years ago. Due to brain damage brought on by meningococcal he now has no short term or picture memory and is legally blind. This is essentially what photography is for me - it\'s seeing stuff and creating memories, often optimistically.\r\n\r\nIt took me a while to figure out that I could shoot for a living. I was working a boring office job but I had the advantage of having a generous boss who gave me flexibility to shoot when I had shoots and work for him when I wasn\'t shooting. It came to a point where I had too many shoots to turn around and no time to work in the office so that was that.\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nWhat style of photography do you specialize in and what are you looking to expand into?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\nI find this a tough question because at a glance I guess some would say I\'m a wedding photographer... but wedding photography, at least good wedding photography, encompasses a range of skills or \"styles\". You need to take on the role of a photojournalist, a fashion shooter, a portrait photographer, a detail/editorial shooter, an interiors photographer, a party photog &amp; be able to get all this within a very limited amount of time. On top of that you’re working with real people, not models! So you\'ve got to think fast and shoot even faster.\r\n\r\nYou\'ve also got to have people skills if the experience is going to be bearable for the client. At the end of the day I believe you need to bring your own creativity &amp; personality to whatever it is you\'re shooting, which is hard to box as one particular style.\r\n<p class=\"spacer\">I have been shooting more and more street photography since moving to New York and that’s something I’ll definitely continue. Most days I will take one lens out and simply wander the streets of Manhattan, looking for stuff. It’s amazing what you begin to see when you start looking. Particularly in a city like this.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote class=\"right\">“Be nice. Don\'t burn people. Be yourself (unless of course you normally burn people in which case don\'t be yourself, just be someone nice).”</blockquote>\r\n<img class=\"left\" src=\"http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/glenallsop-street1.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"333\" height=\"500\" />\r\n<div class=\"caption left\">Olivia Wilde on the street</div>\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nYou photograph luxury cars as you see them on the streets of NYC... what\'s your current top 5 list of luxury cars?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\nYeah there\'s so many nice cars here it\'s insane. In fact, the other day I witnessed a twenty-something year old leave my local brooklyn coffee shop and get into his gunmetal grey V10 Audi R8. I didn\'t know whether to cheer or cry. I used to drive an Audi Avant in Sydney so I always love seeing RS5\'s, RS4 Avants, R8\'s and all their siblings on the streets. Rolls Ghost\'s are fair epic too just when you start thinking about the cost of them and the possibility of who\'s in them. That\'s four. Black Ferrari\'s are also just plain rad. I shot a black Ferrari 458 the other week. That was cool.\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nYour dream client/s?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\nMy dream clients are ones who book me for me. They \"get\" what I do and trust me to see what I see and do what I do. Hopefully Audi or A.P.C will call me soon. Ha. Actually I\'d definitely do contra for Leica too.\r\n<h3 class=\"question clear-left\">Asher:</h3>\r\nWho are some of the photographers you have had the opportunity to work with and who would you like to work with in the future?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\n<p class=\"spacer\">Working with Christian Oth Studio has given me the privilege of shooting alongside and learning from some incredible photographers. I often feel completely out of my league, which is a good place to be. Christian brings a full on creative-fashion-vogue angle to weddings making brides look drop dead gorgeous and he has a unique way of mixing this up with a magnum-esque photojournalists approach. Sometimes I shoot with Mike Falco - he comes from a hardcore NYTimes photojournalism background, and still shoots for the Times - his ability to tell a whole story in one or two pictures is truly a gift.</p>\r\n<img class=\"full-width\" src=\"http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/glenallsop-fullwidth-image.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\n<div class=\"caption full-width\">Bicycle | Brooklyn | Blue</div>\r\nGuy Calaf has a similar thing going on but with an unmatched Italian-Australian-New York intensity. Other days I\'ll be shooting alongside Shawn Connell - he is a phenomenal detail shooter &amp; the way he sees and reads the light continually blows me away. Meredith Davenport is an award winning National Geographic photographer and so on and so on... It\'s starting to read like a PR piece, I know, but I am genuinely so stoked to be working alongside these photographers as they are all legends in their fields and so down-to-earth and yet we all shoot weddings. I think that\'s so cool.\r\n<p class=\"spacer\">If you asked me a year ago who I would like to work with in the future then I wouldn\'t have been able to name any of the names I just mentioned. I don\'t really have a list of who\'s who that I want to work with. It\'s often the unknowns that are so fun &amp; inspiring to work with moreso than the big personalities.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote class=\"full-width line-2 line-2-after\">“It’s amazing what you begin to see when you start looking. Particularly in a city like this.”</blockquote>\r\n<div><img class=\"right\" src=\"http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/glenallsop-audi.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"427\" /></div>\r\n<div class=\"caption right\">Audi A8L in the Meat Packing District</div>\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nWhat is your current set up and what\'s on the wish list?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer clear-left\">Glen:</h3>\r\nHere\'s the list:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>5DmkII</li>\r\n	<li>5D (the original still use this guy cos the colour is just awesome on skin tones. ask any professional photo editor. And the feel of the shutter is this awesome old school \'clunk\'.)</li>\r\n	<li>85mm f1.2 (the fave)</li>\r\n	<li>50mm f1.2</li>\r\n	<li>24-70mm f2.8</li>\r\n	<li>70-200mm f2.8 II (\"the sniper\"... far out this guy is so heavy)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n...and then a few flashes and bits and pieces you know, all in my (now heavy) Billingham 550.\r\nI also shoot 35mm film on a Leica Minilux and an ancient beaten up Canon A2.\r\n\r\nOn the wish list is for Canon to bring out a 35mm f1.2. The 35mm 1.4 is beautiful, but f1.2 is f1.2 and I have this inkling that the moment I buy the f1.4 they\'ll announce the 1.2 and I\'ll be instantly jealous. A lot of readers may not understand that sentence, sorry. Ha. Whilst we\'re on the wish list wagon I\'d throw in a Leica Noctilux 50mm f0.95 (the quickest way to spend $11K) and a Leica M7. Please.\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nDo you have any advice to give fellow photographers looking to expand their client base?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\nWell... I just think if you do a great job and over-deliver then there\'s a better chance you\'ll get a referral. And from referrals come more referrals and so on. Be nice. Don\'t burn people. Be yourself (unless of course you normally burn people in which case don\'t be yourself, just be someone nice).\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nWhat are some of your favourite locations to shoot?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\nI\'ve had some amazing opportunities particularly since working for Christian. The first week I got here Christian sat me down and asked if I was ok to go shoot a wedding in Switzerland in 2 weeks time (\"umm yes\"). That was epic. Besides that we shot a wedding party that went rafting in Jackson Hole Wyoming, an on-stage wedding in a massive old theatre in Texas, a bushfire-smoke-filled few days in Georgia amongst the hanging mossy trees, sunset on the beach in the Hamptons, a lobster picnic dinner for 250 guests in Martha\'s Vineyard... yeah we\'ve seen some amazing stuff.\r\n<p class=\"spacer\">One of my old favourites though is a little place right on the water in Palm Beach, Sydney, called \"The Boathouse\". Sea planes come in and out, the food is perfectly Australian, the atmosphere super relaxed, the sunset is so peaceful and the staff are way too nice to call them \'staff\'. I used to shoot a lot there and that\'s one of the locations I miss the most in Sydney.</p>\r\n<img class=\"full-width\" src=\"http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/glenallsop-fullwidth-image2.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\n<div class=\"caption full-width\">(L) Commuters (R) Malibu wedding</div>\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nWhat new projects you are working on at the moment?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\nA few months ago I set myself the challenge of shooting one-frame-a-day on one camera - a little Leica Minilux 35mm point-and-shoot. It was a great challenge as I have only really started to get into the film side of things since moving to New York and therefore I am learning a lot as I go. At the same time my brother Craig started one a day on a roll of black and white back in Sydney.\r\n\r\nSo now we\'ve just begun posting one day at a time - him in Sydney, me in New York - and we\'ve called it <a title=\"35mm Postcards\" href=\"http://www.35mmPostcards.tumblr.com\" target=\"_blank\">35mm Postcards</a>. First up is the month of December, leading up to Christmas. Its super simple, just a way of saying \"hello\" and the tangible nature of film is a little like a postcard instead of an email I guess. Its been an amazing exercise in slowing down and being extremely decisive and disciplined in what I choose to shoot.\r\n<h3 class=\"question clear-left\">Asher:</h3>\r\nWhat are some of the best things about being a photographer?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\n<p class=\"spacer\">Shooting. I just love shooting. Some days I love it because of the people I meet, some days its the opportunity to shoot something ridiculously amazing, other days I just like the feel of the shutter under my finger, other days its the delayed gratification of not knowing what the picture\'s going to look like until I take another 35 shots to finish the roll and then get it developed. I love it all and wouldn\'t trade it for anything.</p>','Glen Allsop','','publish','closed','closed','glenallsop','glen-allsop','','','2012-04-06 04:56:35','2012-04-06 11:56:35','',0,'http://spiraldesign.ca/?post_type=interview&#038;p=72',0,'interview','',0),(170,1,'2012-03-19 08:16:34','2012-03-19 15:16:34','','redskins','','inherit','open','open','','redskins-2','','','2012-03-19 08:16:34','2012-03-19 15:16:34','',72,'http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/redskins1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(122,1,'2012-03-08 06:09:12','2012-03-08 06:09:12','','interview-image-2','','inherit','open','open','','interview-image-2','','','2012-03-08 06:09:12','2012-03-08 06:09:12','',72,'http://spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/interview-image-2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(74,2,'2012-04-06 03:51:13','2012-04-06 10:51:13','<div><img class=\"right\" src=\"http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/glenallsop.tumblr-2.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"360\" height=\"540\" /></div>\n<div class=\"caption right\" style=\"width: 360px;\">Afternoon light in Soho</div>\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>